      <bioghist id="aspace_ff64e45744b9088e14c2de94fc471ca3">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>Chester F. Wood (1892-1961) graduated from Colby College in 1914 and received a theological education at Newton Theological Institute from 1914-1917 and Harvard University in 1918;. He married Dorthy Shaw (1898-1938) in 1920. Together, they served as Baptist missionaries in Szechuan Province, China in the areas of Chengtu and Suifu from 1920-1926 and 1930-1937. In China, Dorothy ran a local kindergarten and Chester served in churches both in the cities and in the countryside. From 1926-1930, during a time of unrest in China, they returned to the U.S., where Chester served as pastor of East Milton Baptist Church.</p>
      </bioghist>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_3df4b7acb0f58e128282a8513bbb61c6">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The collection contains various ephemera, including cloth and shoes, as well as digital materials containing correspondence, photographs, and an inventory of the artifacts. Further information on the Wood family's life in China can be found in Elizabeth Shaw (Wood) Reed's memoir, My First 76 Years. The collection begins with the written and digital materials and moves into ephemera.</p>
      </scopecontent>
